## 5. Pre-registered failure modes

| ID | Condition |
|---|---|
| F_BS_1 | Subnormal-subnormal pair produces non-integer multiple of `2^(−1074)` — would indicate non-IEEE-conformant arithmetic |
| F_BS_2 | Mixed normal-subnormal pair (a normal, b subnormal) produces non-integer multiple of `ulp(b)` |
| F_BS_3 | Sharpness fails (subnormal a, normal b with k_b > −1022 produces integer differences > 50% — would indicate hidden alignment) |
| F_BS_4 | Hardware-level subnormal-flush-to-zero (FTZ) detected — would invalidate the verification environment |
| F_BS_5 | Proof structure has a hidden dependency on scaling invariance — would mean BACL_subnormal is a separate theorem after all |

## 6. Verification methodology

For each of the following pair classes, sample float values and check that `(a − b) / ulp(b)` is integer to representational precision:

| Class | a | b | n_samples | Expected outcome |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **SubSub** (both subnormal) | random subnormal | random subnormal | 2000 | BACL holds (P_BS_1) |
| **NormSub** (a normal, b subnormal) | random normal | random subnormal | 2000 | BACL holds (P_BS_2) |
| **SubNormSameUlp** (a subnormal, b normal at smallest binade) | random subnormal | random in `[2^−1022, 2·2^−1022)` (smallest normal binade, ulp = 2^−1074) | 2000 | BACL holds (ulp(a) = ulp(b), equality case) |
| **SubNormHigherBinade** (a subnormal, b normal in higher binade) | random subnormal | random in `[2^−1020, 2^−1019)` (binade above smallest, ulp = 2^−1072 > ulp(a)) | 2000 | Hypothesis fails; sharpness expected (P_BS_3) |

Total: ~8000 records.

Additional sanity checks:
